Ver. 0.17.00 - 2008-11-18
    * Fixed bug introduced in 0.15.06.  When the text in the entry
      box was automatically selected, it removed the selection from
      the playlist listbox causing a "No items selected!" message.
    * Use volume percentages for determining whether to bump the PCM
      or the Master volume.
    * Added "Trash missing" button to the Playlist Editor.  This will
      go through the entire playlist and move all entries pointing to
      non-existent files to Trash (playlist "x").  Due to a design
      decision that isn't likely to change, entries cannot be removed
      while the program is running.  However, whenever omp starts, it
      ignores any entries in the playlist that are only in the "x"
      playlist.  When it next saves the playlist, those entries will
      be gone.  Be aware that if you have entries in your playlist
      that point to files on unmounted devices, these will also be
      trashed.  If you want to preserve such files, copy them to a
      special list called "p" (for preserve) and they will be skipped
      in the missing check.
    * Added ability to put a + or - in front of the "Set Rating"
      number in the Playlist Editor.  This will add or subtract
      the given amount to the ratings for the selected entries.
      This makes it easy to adjust an entire album or other grouping
      up or down easily while maintaining the individual differences
      within the group.  You can also end the number with a % sign
      and the adjustment will be a percentage.  If you use only a
      percent sign, then the given percentage will be added as if
      a '+' were in front.  Some examples with the rating before
      adjustment being 0, 50, 100:
      	Input	Ratings after
    	10	10, 10, 10	(as before)
    	+10	10, 60, 100
    	-10	0, 40, 90
    	+10%	0, 55, 100	(same as 10%)
    	-10%	0, 45, 90
      Caveat 1: Integer arithmetic with truncation is used.  Thus +1%
      will never do anything, and -1% will only adjust 100 to 99 and
      not change any other rating.
      Caveat 2: The number part is still limited to 0-100.
      Caveat 3: omp was never intended to be idiot proof.  There is
      no undo.

