Ver. 0.15.05 - 2008-11-01
    * Changed the AgeBonus algorithm.  After trying geometric and
      logarithmic functions, I realized what I really wanted was an
      arctangent curve--one that rises rapidly in the middle and
      flattens out at both ends.  I also thought of a way users can
      easily (well, at least those that know how to program) define
      their own function.  omp will attempt to execute a program
      called agebonus in the ~/.omp directory.  This program should
      return a list of 100 real numbers ranging from 100 down to 0
      on 100 separate lines.  In fact, the program could be a shell
      script with echo statements and the numbers hard-coded.
	  
      Here's what the numbers mean.  omp takes the MinimumAge and
      AgeBonus definitions and converts them to seconds.  It then
      divides the difference of those numbers by 100.  Call the result
      AgePenalty.  For a given rating, it takes the number returned
      by the AgeBonus algorithm and multiplies that times AgePenalty.
      The result is added to the MinimumAge to give a ModifiedMinAge
      which is what omp uses in place of the MinimumAge.  Although my
      algorithm is hard-coded into omp, I have included a sample
      OCaml program, agebonus.ml, that would accomplish the same thing
      if it were compiled and the executable placed in ~/.omp.  I
      have also included agebonus.tcl which does the same thing as
      a TCL script.  You can use whatever language you like as long
      as the output matches the format.  If you have OCaml, you can
      enter "ocaml agebonus.ml" to see the output from that program.
      "tclsh agebonus.tcl" will run the TCL script program.  Actually
      you should be able to set it to an executable and run it
      directly with "./agebonus.tcl".

      If you want to see debug information for ageBonus calculations,
      you can run omp with the "debug" argument.  Note that omp only
      looks at the first argument.

