Ver. 0.15.00 - 2008-10-22
    * Added ^w as an exit key to the main program in addition to ^Escape
      for those whose window managers capture ^Escape.
    * Added NameWidth option.  This allows the user to define the width
      of the name field in the playlist editor.  The default is 70.
    * Changed scrolling name to display the entry as it appears in the
      playlist editor.  Thus one can just about everything omp knows
      about the entry as it plays.
    * Fixed bug where if an entry is locked and then unlocked, it didn't
      recalculate the default increase/decrease for the rating.
    * Fixed bug where if the Playlist editor was closed through the
      window manager, then the Queue editor remained and was hard to
      get rid of.
    * Fixed bug with volume control.  I thought the 0 - 31 limits I saw
      from amixer's output were determined by amixer since it was the
      same on both my computers which have different sound cards.  It
      seems that the limits can vary for other sound cards.  The program
      should correctly handle different limits now.  However, it still
      only uses the PCM and Master channels.  It was designed to move
      the two up alternately using the lowest one to increase.  This
      means if they have different upper limits, one of them will max
      out before the other.  If this is a problem, it could fairly
      easily use percentage comparisons like
        (volPCM / maxPCM) < (volMaster / maxMaster)
      and increase the lower of those.
    * Added Playlist Configuration Editor.  This is called off the old
      Configuration Editor.  Notice the use of Alt- hotkeys.  If I get
      positive feedback on this, I can add it to other windows.  Another
      thought i had was to simply use letters to control the spinboxes.
      E.g., an "S" would increment the font size and a "s" would
      decrement it.  The main reason i didn't is that i wanted the
      sample entry box to be editable so users could type their own
      strings for viewing and i don't think i could keep letters
      entered there from firing the events.  I also thought of using
      Alt-S to decrement the spinbox and Ctrl-S to increment it.  One
      advantage of these two methods is that i could immediately
      display the change in the sample text.  I haven't figured out
      how to capture changes made directly on the widgets.  Anyway,
      for now, you use Alt-S and then the arrow keys.  Alt-F will
      take you to the font selection listbox.  Alt-V will apply the
      changes to the sample text.  I may change all these Alts to
      Ctrls as Ctrl is a lot easier to use on my keyboards.

Ver. 0.14.00 - 2008-10-21
    * Added ^l to Playlist editor to lock selected entries.
    * Added new scheduling option called AgeBonus.
      Here's the problem: I found that my less favorite entries were
      still playing too frequently and my more favorite ones not as
      frequently as I would like.  On the average, it is true my
      favorites will play more frequently over time, but they still
      will not play more frequent than the minimum age.  Yet my
      not-so-favorites could also play just as soon as the minimum
      age in theory.  If an entry fails its rating roll, it must wait
      minimum age again.  It looks like what I want is for the rating
      to not only affect the %age roll, but also the minimum age.  For
      example, I don't mind if my favorite entries play every day, but
      my less favorites I may not want to play more frequently than
      once a month.  However, I don't really want this to be simply
      linear.  For example, I don't really want the MinimumAge for
      a 99% entry to be twice as long as a 100% entry and certainly
      don't want a 90% entry's Min.Age to be 10 times as a long.  So,
      we really need a geometric progression where there is very
      little difference in the min. age near 100 but increases rapidly
      toward 0.

      AgeBonus is an attempt to solve this problem.  AgeBonus uses 2
      numbers: the minimum age for a 100% rated entry (call it Min100),
      and the minimum age for a 1% rated entry (Min1).  My first guess
      at a function was close enough for what I wanted.  Unfortunately,
      I can't think of an easy way for users to define their own
      functions without adding a lot of code.  Anyway, the formula I
      came up with is this:
    	let penalty = (Min100 - Min1) / 100
    	let minimumAge = (100 ** ((100 - entry.rating) / 99)) * penalty
      ('**' is the exponentiation operator in OCaml).
      As you can see, minimumAge will be Min100 for a 100% rating and
      Min1 for a 1% rating.  Just a few numbers to show the progression
      where nx means n times the penalty:
    	90% -> 1.59x, 75% -> 3.2x, 50% -> 10.24x, 25% -> 32.75x.

    To use AgeBonus, set the AgeBonus option (either in omprc or the
    configuration editor) to some *time period* (like MinimumAge)
    greater	than 0 to indicate the minimum age for a 1% rated entry
    (OK, so it is	a bit of a misnomer).  The old MinimumAge value will
    be used as the	minimum age for 100% rated songs.  Obviously,
    AgeBonus must be	greater than MinimumAge or else omp will simply
    use the old selection system.  FWIW, I use "4h" for MinimumAge
    and "21d" for AgeBonus.  The effect was immediately noticeable and
    seems to be very close to what	I wanted.

Ver. 0.13.00 - 2008-10-17
    * Added configuration options NewSkipAge and AutoLock.  Both can be
      left at 0 to disable them.
      If NewSkipAge > 0 then omp will skip the Age check for any entries
        that haven't played more than NewSkipAge times.  This allows new
        entries to play more frequently.
      If AutoLock > 0 then omp will automatically lock the rating for an
        entry after it has played AutoLock number of times.

Ver. 0.12.03 - 2008-10-16
    * Added ability for user to define fonts for the playlist editor.
      The default looked ugly on some systems.  You can add a font= to
      the .omp/omprc file.  Try the following: courier,
      courier 10 pitch, lucidatypewriter, freemono,
      bitstream vera sans mono, terminus, dejavu sans mono, or any
      other fixed space font you may have.  The default is font=fixed.
      You can try different sizes with fontsize=<num>.  The default is
      fontsize=9.  It also defaults to a bold font, if you want a
      normal font, use fontweight=normal.  The default is
      fontweight=bold.

